post_body: His last 24 hours on earth and he’s relaxing outside. First time he’s had energy to leave our house in weeks; I’m glad he got to see it one last time.

Been putting this post off. I wanted to write more but the words aren’t coming. Saturday a week ago we had to send my beloved Smokey across the rainbow bridge. He had been sick over a month and slowly stopped eating and drinking. After multiple vet visits and numerous tests we found he had cancer. Unfortunately his chest and abdominal cavities started filling with fluid so fast we didn’t have time to do more tests to determine treatment. He struggled to breathe. He was slowly starving.   He was suffering and I couldn’t allow that to continue.   My heart is broken. My sweet Smokes had been with us almost 12 years. He was the first cat I had after a few decades of losing my last. He was the best sweetest companion. Even at the end.   He was held in all our hands as he slipped away. He purred until the end. The usual vet we saw wasn’t there so she called us the next day and told us it was the right thing not to wait for her. He was just getting worse and worse.   I miss him every day.   I have his nose prints and paw prints. I will  Be getting those tattooed in the fall as he will always be with me.   Hug your fur babies. You never know when they will be called across the rainbow bridge.

post_body: health update/diatribe/infodump BUT THERE’S A CAT VIDEO AT THE END Dearest reader: This should be a simple health update but instead it’s an obnoxiously detailed info-dump written by the kind of person who knows more than most people about American health insurance but is still surprised at how it continues to find new and innovative ways to suck. If this is not the type of thing your brain or nervous system wants to wrap itself around I don’t blame you one bit but if it is I hope you’ll at least walk away having learned something or being at least mildly entertained. If not feel free to  SCROLL TO THE END FOR A HTDIO-ADJACENT CAT VIDEO! When last we left our third-or-fourth-favorite mildly niche-famous T-list Broadway person she was finally on the brink of getting a brain and pituitary MRI. This was supposed to happen on Friday.  But I wasn’t allowed to get the MRI on Friday because Cigna’s pre-authorization was still pending and there was nothing my doctor could do to escalate its urgency nor could they withdraw the order. They couldn’t do anything at all until the third-party organization that approves the pre-authorizations signed off on its medical necessity.   Look I get it. This is an expensive and labor-intensive procedure so they have to be thorough. I mean sure my doctor said it was medically necessary and sure they sent the additional clinical information to confirm its medically necessity and sure every order at every stage was marked as urgently medically necessary and it was sent for processing on Monday but how can they REALLY be sure it’s medically necessary until my case is also reviewed by doctors who have NEVER seen me and don’t work weekends or holidays and will get around to reviewing it at their own leisure? The folks at the radiology clinic rescheduled me in their next available spot and maintained that they’d contact me as soon as possible to fill any upcoming cancellation spots.  A ridiculous mildly annoying setback was that their next available appointment wasn’t until July 26. They couldn’t attempt to book me at any of the other dozens of clinics affiliated with this hospital network because the pre-authorization is site-specific which is like buying someone a gift card from the Starbucks on my block only to find out that they won’t honor it at the Starbucks two blocks down perfectly reasonable because I’m sure every site has differences that can’t be perceived from a patient perspective.  Oh and the existence of a pending pre-authorization prevented them from doing the MRI that day even if I’d had $8K in cash to pay out of pocket for the procedure. Which is perfectly reasonable because why shouldn’t American healthcare policy punish rich people too? I’m sure it’s many flavors of unethical for one doctor to do something without the approval of another doctor even though the doctor whose approval it hangs on has NEVER SEEN ME.  One fellow in particular–I’ll call him Quincy–gave me some insider info on how to prepare for the types of advocacy he’s had to do in the past with this particular pre-authorization team and which numbers to call and questions to ask. He isn’t technically supposed to know this stuff and also isn’t technically supposed to share it but says he does it all the time anyway–hence why I’m keeping him anonymous. Quincy isn’t his real name but Quincy is a real one and I took in his information like a medieval warrior selecting the choicest armor to prepare for battle the informed and fully compliant patient I strive to be.  Anyway a few persistent phone calls later a Cigna rep informed me that the middlemen would approve the pre-authorization for the MRI on the condition that I get the procedure done at a standalone radiology facility instead of a hospital-affiliated facility. Which is like buying someone a gift card that could only be honored at Starbucks kiosks located inside Target stores but not at a standalone Starbucks or anywhere else in Target perfectly reasonable I know the insurance companies don’t wanna have to spend hospital prices any more than I do. So I spent a great deal of time yesterday looking up non-hospital-affiliated radiology clinics that were in-network.  I made an appointment with one clinic for Thursday. But I also made an appointment request at a different clinic for Monday morning just in case they could see me sooner–because I knew this clinic didn’t accept Medicare or Medicaid and were therefore exempt from the requirement of third-party pre-authorization. (Pro-tip: even if you do have Medicare or Medicaid always try to bypass pre-authorization for diagnostic procedures especially if you have a particularly high in-network deductible–it’s entirely possible that paying out of pocket for a service at an out-of-network provider could cost less than the amount you’d have to pay towards your deductible at at in-network facility. American math.)  THIS MORNING I woke up at 8am to a phone call from the latter clinic saying that if I sent them the doctor’s prescription they could pre-authorize the procedure and see me tomorrow. So that’s what I did…and then I got an email saying that they couldn’t accept a prescription for an MRI with and without contrast because they don’t have contrast at that facility. Which is like finally securing a coveted reservation at an elite steakhouse only to find out they don’t season their steak or even have steak sauce perfectly reasonable because not everyone needs contrast but I do so that place was out.  But as far as I’ve been told Thursday’s appointment should go off without a hitch as long as I call EviCore (the pre-authorization middlemen) tomorrow morning to tell them all about the not-hospital that will be giving me a not-hospital-priced MRI so that they can grant the pre-authorization at long last.  Perhaps if I plead my case and bat my eyes at them real cute-like through the phone  they’ll give me some other reason why it’s actually not medically necessary for me to know definitively whether or not I have a literal brain tumor I can get seen even sooner than Thursday.  FUNNY STORY THOUGH…  A couple weeks ago I was talking to a friend from church who was going through a lot of the same stuff as I was and I was like “idk maybe get your cortisol checked?” and lo and behold he messaged me back a few days ago saying that he’d found a new doctor and asked him to do just that and WITHIN A DAY his doctor ordered ALL the labs I’d fought for (serum blood cortisol low-dose dexamethasone suppression test 24-hour urine saliva etc.) AND an MRI for suspected Cushing’s.  And he completed ALL OF THAT within a week.  Although he did have to suffer for quite a while before I floated the possibility of Cushing’s just like my friend Alan had to suffer for years before his own endocrinologists floated the possibility of Cushing’s. Still they both got that MRI the second it WAS floated without a fight and I’m genuinely happy for them.  But I can’t help wondering how much quicker and easier this whole process would have been for me if I were a man. Or if I was neurotypical. Or if I still had a choice about whether or not to disclose being autistic. But mostly if I were a man.  THIS IS THE END! HERE IS THE HTDIO-ADJACENT CAT VIDEO YOU WERE PROMISED! I’m fostering my friends’ exquisite tuxedo princessfloof for a few weeks. Chevy and Tex are being very accommodating foster siblings but she’s much younger and is used to being the only pet so naturally it took her a while to acclimate.  But there was one thing she took to immediately: the How to Dance in Ohio fidget spinner.
I’m never getting this done.

But I can’t help wondering how much quicker and easier this whole process would have been for me if I were a man. Or if I was neurotypical. Or if I still had a choice about whether or not to disclose being autistic. But mostly if I were a man.  THIS IS THE END! HERE IS THE HTDIO-ADJACENT CAT VIDEO YOU WERE PROMISED! I’m fostering my friends’ exquisite tuxedo princessfloof for a few weeks. Chevy and Tex are being very accommodating foster siblings but she’s much younger and is used to being the only pet so naturally it took her a while to acclimate.  But there was one thing she took to immediately: the How to Dance in Ohio fidget spinner.
I’m never getting this done.

post_body: The picture I took  The picture I ended up posting
Void

Introduction Post That’s my cat. His name is Infurno.   Updated Name: I’m searching for a new online name because I got bored of the old one. Give me suggestions.  I am an adult but I don’t act like one.   I have depression adhd and a manic-depressive disorder. I am medicated for all of them but I still have mood swings. If I sound abnormally despairing it’s probably just a down swing. However if you feel the need to reach out to me I usually don’t mind. However I may then send you cat memes randomly for the next few weeks.   Please note that I often struggle to communicate and understand other people especially online where I can’t hear your voice. I may have to ask rather foolish questions.   Here is another photo of my cat.  Hobbies? Every once in a while I’ll write something. I’m more likely to write if people bug me about it. Feel free to complain if I don’t respond to your tag.  I also enjoy photography. What I take pictures of varies depending on the season and my surroundings. However the one constant is that I will always take pictures of my cat.  Sometimes I spend all day everyday reading sometimes I don’t read for months on end. There is no in-between.   Current hyper-focuses? Stardew valley. (Don’t ask me how many hours I have played. It’s too many.)  Psychology!   Have a few more pictures of my cat.

I am an adult but I don’t act like one.   I have depression adhd and a manic-depressive disorder. I am medicated for all of them but I still have mood swings. However I may then send you cat memes randomly for the next few weeks.   Please note that I often struggle to communicate and understand other people especially online where I can’t hear your voice. I may have to ask rather foolish questions.   Here is another photo of my cat.  Hobbies? Every once in a while I’ll write something. I’m more likely to write if people bug me about it. Feel free to complain if I don’t respond to your tag.  I also enjoy photography. What I take pictures of varies depending on the season and my surroundings. post_body: Posting my cat until I get bored. Day 8.

Hey there everyone  For those who had been following along in regard to the recent situation here I had to go back to the vet with both Oreo and Pudding yesterday. Oreo has been throwing up a lot this past week and I was concerned. Pudding also threw up yesterday. He threw up his entire lunch right after he ate and there was a big hairball stuck inside. I was concerned that maybe the yarn would surface next. So far it hasn’t.  Oreo did some blood tests as well as another X-ray. His iron levels are almost back to normal which is great but the tests also show that he has some sort of infection. The vet isn’t sure what it is but most likely from everything he just recently went through. He was given an atibiotic injection as well as an anti-nausea injection. I also have some anti-nausea pills for him for 4 days. We will see how the antibiotic does and if he still continues to throw up he wil have to see a specialist for an ultrasound. There was nothing out of the ordinary in his X-ray.  Pudding was checked too and everything seems OK with him. I hope that Oreo will feel better with the antibiotic and we won’t have to see the specialist. If we do we will have to make the trek to Montreal and it will cost a few thousand dollars. I will keep you posted on what happens next. Let’s everyone keep our fingers and paws crossed that this will be the end of it.  Thanks to everyone for your kind words prayers and continued support. They’re sincerely appreciated.  Tina.

post_body: Some humans are just fucking retards… This is a personal rant as I cannot vent my frustration anywhere else without getting in trouble so here goes.  So something came up recently with one of our cats. His name is Cheddar and orange and white cat. He quite literally ‘came out of the Matrix’ as my mom put it as he came out of nowhere and lodged with us. He was the friendliest cat I’d ever met and very playful as orange cats do. Funny thing is he was estimated to only be about a year old and not neutered so we don’t know why he was so comfortable with us.  Now you’ve probably noticed that I’m using 'was’ instead of 'is’.  Cheddar Cheese is dead.  He had to be put down because get this:  He was SHOT.  Apparently some douchebag with a vendetta against cats saw Cheddar and decided “Hey why don’t I go shoot that cat for funnsies? That’ll be a hoot!” and shot Ched in the leg paralyzing his back right leg. We don’t know where this happened but we can assume it happened somewhere far enough that due to Cheddar dragging his foot against the ground resulted in sores forming due to the fur being pulled away.  We originally thought some of the neighborhood cats got to him as our oldest cat tends to get into fights and is covered in scabs and wounds 90% of the time but we were wrong.  I am rightfully angered by the news as is my younger brother who’d come to love that cat immensely over the few months we had Cheddar. Unfortunately we aren’t allowed to show our anger or emotions in this household because the second I started clenching my fists my dad immediately put an end to it. Heck he wouldn’t even let my brother vent his frustration out on his boxing stand for Celestia’s sake! Like come on just let the poor kid vent it he just lost a beloved pet!  Now I’m worried. There’s someone in my neighborhood who would just shoot a cat for no damn reason other than they just can. If this happened to Cheddar I’m worried it’ll happen to the other two…  I haven’t been hit as hard by the news as everyone else but I’m devastated and rightfully pissed the fuck off. Who would just see an innocent pet and shoot them for fucks sake?! You most likely saw the collar around his neck you fuckard! So why’d you do it huh?!  Why’d you do it?

post_body: The camera is almost a Monty long
Matilda in the morning.  Not the best quality I’m so sorry.

A year ago Peridot came home with me from the shelterALTALT She was about 7lbs. She had been surrendered from her previous family due to bathroom issues they assumed was anxiety.   It’s been a wonderful year.  She got to a healthy weight we found her food that she isn’t allergic to.   Peri is an extremely clever cat who knows when I’m upset and will try to comfort me. She will lay on me differently when I’m in pain to not hurt my body as bad. She’s learned she can lay on my left arm when I’m working so I can still type (right is free to go back and forth between mouse and keyboard).   She’s made art (with some help from some catnip).  She’s inspired some of my art.   Peri loves to snuggle. She’s excited when I sit on the couch after work to sit on my lap. She comes in the morning when she realizes I’m awake to get morning pets.   We love each other so much. I can’t imagine the last year without her. We found each other in a scary place in both of our lives and we are both doing better.   ALTALTALTALTALTALTALTALTHappy Birthday Peridot! I love you so much! 💚💚💚

A year ago Peridot came home with me from the shelterALTALT She was about 7lbs. She had been surrendered from her previous family due to bathroom issues they assumed was anxiety.   It’s been a wonderful year.  She got to a healthy weight we found her food that she isn’t allergic to.   Peri is an extremely clever cat who knows when I’m upset and will try to comfort me. She will lay on me differently when I’m in pain to not hurt my body as bad. She’s learned she can lay on my left arm when I’m working so I can still type (right is free to go back and forth between mouse and keyboard).   She’s made art (with some help from some catnip).  She’s inspired some of my art.   Peri loves to snuggle. She’s excited when I sit on the couch after work to sit on my lap. She comes in the morning when she realizes I’m awake to get morning pets.   We love each other so much. I can’t imagine the last year without her. We found each other in a scary place in both of our lives and we are both doing better.   ALTALTALTALTALTALTALTALTHappy Birthday Peridot! I love you so much! 💚💚💚
